title: Episode 86 – “Vote Climate” with Jacquelyn Francis, Founder & E.D., Keeling Curve Prize
subtitle: Sarah Arao Mantle of Hope- Thank You Video to the Y on Earth Community for GoFundMe Campaign Support
description: Welcome to the YonEarth Community Podcast. I’m your host, Aaron William Perry. And today we’re visiting with the Executive Director of the Keeling Curve Prize, Jacquelyn Francis. Hi Jacquelyn.
full_transcript:
[11.3s - 17.3s]: Welcome to the Why on Earth Community Podcast. I'm your host, Aaron William Perry. And today,

[17.5s - 22.9s]: we're visiting with the Executive Director of the Keeling Curve Prize, Jacqueline Francis.

[23.4s - 28.0s]: Hi Jacqueline. Hi Aaron, how are you? I'm doing great. How are you doing today?

[28.9s - 34.2s]: I'm doing well. Happy to be here. Yeah, excellent. I'm really looking forward to our conversation

[34.2s - 41.9s]: and sharing that with our audience. Jacqueline is both the creator and the Executive Director of the

[41.9s - 48.1s]: Keeling Curve Prize and a board member of the overarching organization, the Global Warming

[48.1s - 54.9s]: Mitigation Project. While earning a master's degree in energy policy and climate from Johns Hopkins

[54.9s - 61.0s]: University, she became concerned with the slow pace, climate solutions were being adopted and

[61.0s - 68.0s]: implemented and the lack of progress towards global carbon emissions reduction. She decided that

[68.0s - 74.5s]: more needed to be done to accelerate the shift to a climate stable future and using her background

[74.5s - 80.8s]: connections and expertise started the prize. She has built a network of scientists and experts

[80.8s - 87.2s]: devoted to action, spoke at the Explorers Club in New York City, became involved with the TED

[87.2s - 93.1s]: community in Vancouver and was awarded half a million dollars to international climate solutions.

[94.3s - 100.1s]: Prior to the Keeling Curve Prize, Jackie ran a pilot program for the Smithsonian Science Education

[100.1s - 106.0s]: Center about emergent scientific learning alongside world renowned physicist David Pines.

[107.0s - 112.3s]: She spent four years as the Executive Director of the Aspen Science Center working closely with

[112.3s - 118.0s]: the Aspen Center for Physics. She coordinated a program for the US Department of Energy under Steven

[118.0s - 125.0s]: Chiu and has been instrumental in spurring action surrounding any energy solutions for decades.

[126.1s - 131.1s]: Yeah, wow Jacqueline, that's quite a lot that you've already accomplished there and clearly have been

[131.7s - 137.4s]: collaborating with some very interesting folks. I want to kick off by just asking

[138.6s - 145.3s]: a very straight up question, what is the Keeling Curve prize and for our audience, let's assume most

[145.3s - 151.8s]: haven't yet heard about Keeling Curve prize. Tell us what it's all about and how it's helping our

[151.8s - 157.3s]: situation in the world. Okay, yeah, sure. And there's one thing that I want to correct on my bio.

[157.3s - 161.5s]: It's so fun to actually listen to my bio because I'm like, oh yeah, I do do that. Oh, and I did that too.

[161.9s - 168.2s]: But we've given away $750,000 to date because we just had our award ceremony this summer and I guess

[168.2s - 175.7s]: I need to update that. But it's been really exciting to like be able to fund projects and programs

[175.7s - 184.9s]: around the world that are actively addressing emissions and carbon uptake. So the Keeling Curve,

[184.9s - 192.0s]: for those of you who don't know, is the data set that was started in 1958 by Charles David Keeling

[192.7s - 200.8s]: that measures greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, specifically CO2. And it was featured in the

[201.8s - 209.1s]: inconvenient truth movie as that graph that just kind of slowly, not slowly actually, it's been

[209.1s - 216.8s]: going up ever since it's been measured. And it kind of has a squiggly squigglyness to it for the

[216.8s - 225.4s]: the breathing of the earth, the summer and the winter emissions kind of fluctuation. So we, I

[226.4s - 232.9s]: called Ralph Keeling who's the son of Charles David Keeling a few years ago and I said, hey, I want

[232.9s - 239.4s]: to start this prize that actually acknowledges organizations that are doing something about greenhouse

[239.4s - 246.9s]: gases. Can we name it after the Keeling Curve, the data set? And his family said yes. And Ralph is

[246.9s - 252.6s]: now one of our advisory council members. He's actually been on since the beginning. And his family

[252.6s - 260.3s]: and his mother, who's the wife of Charles David Keeling, is very proud of the prize, which is giving

[260.3s - 268.2s]: out money globally to organizations that are doing doing the work. Beautiful. Yeah. And so this is a

[268.9s - 274.4s]: there's a competitive process right with multiple categories. And is it it's an annual cycle?

[274.5s - 283.7s]: Is that how that works? Yeah, it is an annual cycle. And the 2021 application process is opening

[283.7s - 290.8s]: November 1st. So that's coming up. And people apply from all over the world. Last year we limited

[290.8s - 296.2s]: the applicants to 300, but this year I think we're going to open it up to more because we did we did

[388.2s - 395.6s]: interesting to see the evolution in that arena right now. There is evolution, but it still needs

[406.1s - 412.7s]: one of the areas that really need a lot of activation and elevation. Yeah no doubt about it.

segments.text: Welcome to the Why on Earth Community Podcast. I'm your host, Aaron William Perry. And today,
we're visiting with the Executive Director of the Keeling Curve Prize, Jacqueline Francis.
Hi Jacqueline. Hi Aaron, how are you? I'm doing great. How are you doing today?
I'm doing well. Happy to be here. Yeah, excellent. I'm really looking forward to our conversation
and sharing that with our audience. Jacqueline is both the creator and the Executive Director of the
Keeling Curve Prize and a board member of the overarching organization, the Global Warming
Mitigation Project. While earning a master's degree in energy policy and climate from Johns Hopkins
University, she became concerned with the slow pace, climate solutions were being adopted and
implemented and the lack of progress towards global carbon emissions reduction. She decided that
more needed to be done to accelerate the shift to a climate stable future and using her background
connections and expertise started the prize. She has built a network of scientists and experts
devoted to action, spoke at the Explorers Club in New York City, became involved with the TED
community in Vancouver and was awarded half a million dollars to international climate solutions.
Prior to the Keeling Curve Prize, Jackie ran a pilot program for the Smithsonian Science Education
Center about emergent scientific learning alongside world renowned physicist David Pines.
She spent four years as the Executive Director of the Aspen Science Center working closely with
the Aspen Center for Physics. She coordinated a program for the US Department of Energy under Steven
Chiu and has been instrumental in spurring action surrounding any energy solutions for decades.
Yeah, wow Jacqueline, that's quite a lot that you've already accomplished there and clearly have been
collaborating with some very interesting folks. I want to kick off by just asking
a very straight up question, what is the Keeling Curve prize and for our audience, let's assume most
haven't yet heard about Keeling Curve prize. Tell us what it's all about and how it's helping our
situation in the world. Okay, yeah, sure. And there's one thing that I want to correct on my bio.
It's so fun to actually listen to my bio because I'm like, oh yeah, I do do that. Oh, and I did that too.
But we've given away $750,000 to date because we just had our award ceremony this summer and I guess
I need to update that. But it's been really exciting to like be able to fund projects and programs
around the world that are actively addressing emissions and carbon uptake. So the Keeling Curve,
for those of you who don't know, is the data set that was started in 1958 by Charles David Keeling
that measures greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, specifically CO2. And it was featured in the
inconvenient truth movie as that graph that just kind of slowly, not slowly actually, it's been
going up ever since it's been measured. And it kind of has a squiggly squigglyness to it for the
the breathing of the earth, the summer and the winter emissions kind of fluctuation. So we, I
called Ralph Keeling who's the son of Charles David Keeling a few years ago and I said, hey, I want
to start this prize that actually acknowledges organizations that are doing something about greenhouse
gases. Can we name it after the Keeling Curve, the data set? And his family said yes. And Ralph is
now one of our advisory council members. He's actually been on since the beginning. And his family
and his mother, who's the wife of Charles David Keeling, is very proud of the prize, which is giving
out money globally to organizations that are doing doing the work. Beautiful. Yeah. And so this is a
there's a competitive process right with multiple categories. And is it it's an annual cycle?
Is that how that works? Yeah, it is an annual cycle. And the 2021 application process is opening
November 1st. So that's coming up. And people apply from all over the world. Last year we limited
the applicants to 300, but this year I think we're going to open it up to more because we did we did
fill our quota. And we have five categories. It's capture and utilization, which includes
like regenerative agriculture and natural solutions as well as high tech solutions like direct air

and that can be everything from avoiding transportation to innovation in transportation and you know
mobility systems. Social and cultural pathways and that can be like education. It can be
the journalism. It can be activism. All kinds of things like that. Energy and especially
addressing renewable energy in places where there is energy poverty. And then finance. And
finance is an interesting one because financial mechanisms are just so important in all aspects of
funding climate solutions and they traditionally haven't been great and they are getting much better.
Yeah, indeed some of my friends and colleagues in the finance sector are actually seeing more and
more opportunities to invest in disruptive technologies, innovative solutions. And so it's really
interesting to see the evolution in that arena right now. There is evolution, but it still needs
needs a long way to go and there needs to be one of the things that I say we do with the killing
curve prizes. We activate and accelerate climate action and climate solutions and in finance that's
one of the areas that really need a lot of activation and elevation. Yeah no doubt about it.
Well, let me sort of back up a little bit here and ask you about the origins of all this and
really before the organization got rolling your own personal journey coming to this kind of work.
And I know you shared with me before we started recording that you have two daughters in their
early 20s, roughly similar ages to my two kids. And I'd love to hear you share a bit about that
kind of more personal side of the story as it brought you to where you are today.
You know, there is something about having kids that makes you think about the future and what
we're doing to the planet. So I do appreciate all the people that get involved with climate solutions
that maybe don't have kids or aren't planning on having kids, but I think that for me personally,
when I have my first child, I attended something when she was just a baby called the State of
the World Conference. And at this conference, some people like Bill McKibbin were there speaking and
General Wesley Clark and some others that have been in this space for a long time, you know,
Wilson. And I started listening to some of the messages that they were discussing and what the
state of what was happening with the State of the World. And it made me very concerned. And I

So we need to get out there and get busy and start working on
climate action, climate solutions and becoming a problem solver when it came to such a big problem.

Yes, I believe so.
Yeah, so yeah, from your perspective, tell us a little more about it. What is it and why is it

Well, there was several kind of precursors to the Paris Climate Accord, the talks in Kyoto and
the Kyoto Protocol and then the Copenhagen talks. And Paris was so it was so symbolic because
most of the countries in the world really did work hard to come together on something that was just,

Absolutely. Yeah, it's absolutely right. So I'm really excited to share with our audience this
